00:00:58.186 --> 00:01:00.316 A:middle
and this is a framework
that will allow you

00:01:00.316 --> 00:01:03.646 A:middle
to build a photo editing
extension, app extension,

00:01:03.876 --> 00:01:06.726 A:middle
that can be used right within
the built-in Photos app.

00:01:09.716 --> 00:01:12.966 A:middle
So, in this session we're
going to focus first

00:01:12.966 --> 00:01:17.196 A:middle
on how you can use the
Photos Framework to fetch

00:01:17.196 --> 00:01:19.146 A:middle
and manipulate photo
library model data,

00:01:19.606 --> 00:01:23.786 A:middle
handle external changes, and
both retrieve and edit photo

00:01:23.786 --> 00:01:26.806 A:middle
and video content in
the iOS 8 photo library.

00:01:28.046 --> 00:01:29.706 A:middle
Then we're going to
turn our attention

00:01:29.736 --> 00:01:33.596 A:middle
to the PhotosUI Framework and
walk you through the steps

00:01:33.596 --> 00:01:36.296 A:middle
and the concepts you need
to understand in order

00:01:36.296 --> 00:01:38.566 A:middle
to build your own app extension

00:01:38.566 --> 00:01:40.546 A:middle
for editing photo
and video content.

00:01:42.666 --> 00:01:43.726 A:middle
All right.

00:01:43.726 --> 00:01:46.146 A:middle
So, let's get started
with the Photos Framework.

00:01:46.856 --> 00:01:53.406 A:middle
The Photos Framework is a new
Objective-C framework in iOS 8.

00:01:54.256 --> 00:01:59.366 A:middle
And it allows you to make
your application a first-class

00:01:59.366 --> 00:02:03.736 A:middle
citizen of the system photo
library for everything,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:59.366 --> 00:02:03.736 A:middle
citizen of the system photo
library for everything,

00:02:03.736 --> 00:02:06.126 A:middle
from something simple
like a custom image picker

00:02:06.126 --> 00:02:08.026 A:middle
in your application to going

00:02:08.026 --> 00:02:11.846 A:middle
and building a full-featured
custom application

00:02:11.846 --> 00:02:14.286 A:middle
for browsing the photo
library and editing.

00:02:15.356 --> 00:02:19.096 A:middle
And we really believe in this

00:02:19.096 --> 00:02:22.746 A:middle
because we're using the Photos
Framework in our own Photos

00:02:22.746 --> 00:02:25.456 A:middle
and Camera applications
that are built-in in iOS 8.

00:02:25.966 --> 00:02:29.036 A:middle
For those of you who have
worked with photos in the past,

00:02:29.726 --> 00:02:31.546 A:middle
this Photos Framework
is designed

00:02:31.596 --> 00:02:33.536 A:middle
to supersede the
ALAssetsLibrary,

00:02:33.536 --> 00:02:34.756 A:middle
which doesn't provide,

00:02:35.516 --> 00:02:41.096 A:middle
[ Laughter and Applause ]

00:02:41.596 --> 00:02:44.126 A:middle
which doesn't provide much of
the functionality and features

00:02:44.126 --> 00:02:45.616 A:middle
that you'll get with
the Photos Framework.

00:02:47.076 --> 00:02:50.626 A:middle
So what do you get with
the Photos Framework?

00:02:50.986 --> 00:02:53.056 A:middle
You get access to
photo and video assets,

00:02:53.056 --> 00:02:56.126 A:middle
albums and moments,
something you didn't get

00:02:56.126 --> 00:02:57.116 A:middle
with the assets library.

00:02:57.676 --> 00:03:03.976 A:middle
And then you can also
add, remove, modify assets


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:57.676 --> 00:03:03.976 A:middle
And then you can also
add, remove, modify assets

00:03:03.976 --> 00:03:06.596 A:middle
and albums right in the
system-wide photo library.

00:03:07.286 --> 00:03:12.336 A:middle
You can then also edit photo
and video content and metadata

00:03:12.696 --> 00:03:15.706 A:middle
that is written directly into
the system photo library.

00:03:17.776 --> 00:03:19.086 A:middle
We're excited about it, too.

00:03:19.086 --> 00:03:19.696 A:middle
That's okay.

00:03:20.246 --> 00:03:24.856 A:middle
So, we're going to walk through
this API in a couple of steps.

00:03:24.856 --> 00:03:27.746 A:middle
The first section is going
to focus on the model data

00:03:27.906 --> 00:03:30.486 A:middle
and this is going to
walk you through how

00:03:30.486 --> 00:03:33.746 A:middle
to fetch the model objects,
how to change model data,

00:03:34.116 --> 00:03:35.876 A:middle
how to handle external changes.

00:03:36.216 --> 00:03:38.576 A:middle
And then we'll turn our
attention to working

00:03:38.576 --> 00:03:41.816 A:middle
with the image and video
content of those assets,

00:03:42.686 --> 00:03:46.266 A:middle
how to retrieve it efficiently,
and tips for working

00:03:46.266 --> 00:03:49.646 A:middle
with different types of image
and video content, and then how

00:03:49.646 --> 00:03:51.226 A:middle
to go ahead and make changes

00:03:51.616 --> 00:03:53.556 A:middle
and apply those back
to the photo library.

00:03:54.246 --> 00:03:57.716 A:middle
So I'm going to start off
looking at model data.

00:03:58.506 --> 00:04:01.736 A:middle
So, model data in the Photos
Framework is represented


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:58.506 --> 00:04:01.736 A:middle
So, model data in the Photos
Framework is represented

00:04:01.736 --> 00:04:03.586 A:middle
with what we call model objects.

00:04:03.696 --> 00:04:07.006 A:middle
And these represent the
structure of the photo library.

00:04:07.426 --> 00:04:10.196 A:middle
These are the records
that represent photo

00:04:10.196 --> 00:04:13.756 A:middle
and video assets, moments,
albums and folders.

00:04:14.806 --> 00:04:19.086 A:middle
And the key concept I want you
to take away from this section,

00:04:19.755 --> 00:04:23.556 A:middle
one of the key concepts is that
model objects that are presented

00:04:23.556 --> 00:04:25.696 A:middle
in the Photo Framework
are read-only,

00:04:25.926 --> 00:04:30.206 A:middle
and that is a nice benefit
because it means you can work

00:04:30.206 --> 00:04:32.246 A:middle
with those objects in
a thread-safe manner.

00:04:32.246 --> 00:04:34.616 A:middle
You can pass them between
threads without worrying

00:04:34.616 --> 00:04:36.656 A:middle
about their data changing
out from underneath you.

00:04:37.096 --> 00:04:42.086 A:middle
There's no worries about locking
and handling concurrent changes.

00:04:43.476 --> 00:04:47.176 A:middle
So I'd like to walk through
the different model objects

00:04:47.176 --> 00:04:50.876 A:middle
that we provide with an
illustration using the built-in

00:04:50.876 --> 00:04:52.576 A:middle
iOS 8 Photos application.

00:04:53.676 --> 00:04:55.446 A:middle
So we'll start with the assets.

00:04:55.826 --> 00:04:57.106 A:middle
These are the photos and videos

00:04:57.106 --> 00:04:58.926 A:middle
that you see here
in the Photos App.

00:04:58.926 --> 00:05:04.546 A:middle
And then containing assets,
we have at the next level up,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:58.926 --> 00:05:04.546 A:middle
And then containing assets,
we have at the next level up,

00:05:05.086 --> 00:05:07.846 A:middle
Asset Collections, what
we call Asset Collections

00:05:07.846 --> 00:05:08.756 A:middle
in the Photos Framework.

00:05:09.426 --> 00:05:13.236 A:middle
And in the case we're looking
at a view that shows moments.

00:05:13.236 --> 00:05:16.126 A:middle
And a moment is comprised
of a collection of assets.

00:05:16.676 --> 00:05:20.496 A:middle
At the next level above that,

00:05:21.246 --> 00:05:23.566 A:middle
we have what we call
Collection Lists,

00:05:23.896 --> 00:05:26.196 A:middle
and these are lists
of Asset Collections.

00:05:26.606 --> 00:05:28.236 A:middle
And in the case you're
looking at here,

00:05:28.236 --> 00:05:31.526 A:middle
we're seeing the year moment
view, which is comprised

00:05:31.526 --> 00:05:32.716 A:middle
of a series of moments,

00:05:32.816 --> 00:05:35.796 A:middle
which then in turn are
comprised of assets.

00:05:38.236 --> 00:05:41.416 A:middle
Now let's walk through
these Model Objects in terms

00:05:41.416 --> 00:05:43.076 A:middle
of the APIs that
are exposed to you

00:05:43.076 --> 00:05:44.146 A:middle
through the Photos Framework.

00:05:44.776 --> 00:05:46.676 A:middle
The first one we'll
look at is the Assets,

00:05:46.676 --> 00:05:47.686 A:middle
the photos and videos.

00:05:48.226 --> 00:05:51.016 A:middle
And photos and videos
assets are represented

00:05:51.016 --> 00:05:52.696 A:middle
by the PHAsset class.

00:05:53.816 --> 00:05:57.236 A:middle
And as you look through this
UI in the Photos Application,

00:05:57.236 --> 00:05:59.266 A:middle
you can see it's a photo.

00:05:59.266 --> 00:06:00.266 A:middle
That's the media type.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:59.266 --> 00:06:00.266 A:middle
That's the media type.

00:06:01.446 --> 00:06:02.286 A:middle
But then at the top

00:06:02.286 --> 00:06:05.096 A:middle
of the screen you can see we're
displaying the creation date

00:06:05.096 --> 00:06:08.116 A:middle
and the location, which are
both properties of the asset.

00:06:09.106 --> 00:06:11.966 A:middle
Down at the bottom of the screen
you can see an icon representing

00:06:12.256 --> 00:06:14.796 A:middle
a heart, that is, whether

00:06:14.796 --> 00:06:16.766 A:middle
that asset has been
marked as a favorite.

00:06:17.386 --> 00:06:19.436 A:middle
And these are all
properties available to you

00:06:19.436 --> 00:06:21.296 A:middle
in the model object, PHAsset.

00:06:21.726 --> 00:06:25.756 A:middle
At the next level
up we're talking

00:06:25.756 --> 00:06:27.586 A:middle
about the Asset Collection
and, again,

00:06:27.586 --> 00:06:29.466 A:middle
we're illustrating
that with the moment.

00:06:29.846 --> 00:06:34.176 A:middle
An Asset Collection is a general
ordered collection of assets,

00:06:34.326 --> 00:06:35.596 A:middle
so there are a couple
of different types.

00:06:35.596 --> 00:06:37.706 A:middle
We've got moments,
like you can see here.

00:06:37.706 --> 00:06:40.266 A:middle
But we also have
albums and smart albums.

00:06:40.776 --> 00:06:44.246 A:middle
The Asset Collection,
unsurprisingly,

00:06:44.546 --> 00:06:47.676 A:middle
represented by the
PHAssetCollection class,

00:06:48.246 --> 00:06:50.916 A:middle
and it has the properties
of the type, title,

00:06:51.516 --> 00:06:52.566 A:middle
and start and end date.

00:06:52.566 --> 00:06:54.676 A:middle
And you can see these
properties reflected in the UI.

00:06:56.816 --> 00:07:00.606 A:middle
Going one level higher, we
have the Collection List.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:56.816 --> 00:07:00.606 A:middle
Going one level higher, we
have the Collection List.

00:07:01.316 --> 00:07:04.556 A:middle
And a Collection List
is an ordered collection

00:07:04.556 --> 00:07:05.456 A:middle
of collections.

00:07:05.796 --> 00:07:08.776 A:middle
And in the case we're looking at
here, we've got a moment year.

00:07:09.316 --> 00:07:11.086 A:middle
But you can also have
a Collection List

00:07:11.086 --> 00:07:12.556 A:middle
that represents a folder.

00:07:13.166 --> 00:07:15.426 A:middle
And something that's
unique about a folder

00:07:15.426 --> 00:07:19.026 A:middle
versus a moment year type
of Collection List is

00:07:19.026 --> 00:07:21.796 A:middle
that a folder can
actually contain subfolders

00:07:21.946 --> 00:07:23.276 A:middle
as well as albums.

00:07:23.436 --> 00:07:27.486 A:middle
So that's why we say an ordered
collection of collections

00:07:27.486 --> 00:07:30.316 A:middle
where those collections
might be an Asset Collection

00:07:30.866 --> 00:07:32.716 A:middle
or a Collection List.

00:07:33.316 --> 00:07:38.306 A:middle
The Collection List class
is the PHCollectionList and,

00:07:38.306 --> 00:07:40.166 A:middle
similar to the Asset
Collection, has a type,

00:07:40.716 --> 00:07:44.916 A:middle
title and a start and end date.

00:07:46.086 --> 00:07:48.306 A:middle
So when you want to work
with these model objects,

00:07:48.836 --> 00:07:50.726 A:middle
you need to get them out
of the photo library.

00:07:51.296 --> 00:07:55.466 A:middle
So, in order to get
these model objects

00:07:55.466 --> 00:07:58.576 A:middle
out of the photo library, the
key concept here that I want you

00:07:58.656 --> 00:08:00.626 A:middle
to focus on in this
section for fetching,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:58.656 --> 00:08:00.626 A:middle
to focus on in this
section for fetching,

00:08:00.626 --> 00:08:05.236 A:middle
is that you use the class
methods on the model object

00:08:05.236 --> 00:08:06.256 A:middle
that you want to fetch out.

00:08:06.846 --> 00:08:08.916 A:middle
So when you want to
fetch out assets - say,

00:08:08.916 --> 00:08:10.766 A:middle
you wanted to fetch all
of the video assets -

00:08:11.696 --> 00:08:14.536 A:middle
you look for the class
method on the PHAsset class,

00:08:14.616 --> 00:08:20.486 A:middle
fetchAssetsWithMediaType,
specifying the media type video.

00:08:20.656 --> 00:08:22.986 A:middle
Similarly, as I said before,

00:08:22.986 --> 00:08:24.906 A:middle
a moment is a type
of Asset Collection.

00:08:25.236 --> 00:08:28.446 A:middle
So to fetch moments,
we use a class method

00:08:28.446 --> 00:08:32.576 A:middle
on the Asset Collection class,
to fetchMomentsWithOptions.

00:08:33.476 --> 00:08:36.635 A:middle
Now in both of these examples
I've omitted the options,

00:08:36.986 --> 00:08:39.856 A:middle
but they give you an opportunity
to do things like filter

00:08:39.856 --> 00:08:42.446 A:middle
or sort the results
that you get back.

00:08:44.606 --> 00:08:48.496 A:middle
So the next key concept
I want to cover as far

00:08:48.496 --> 00:08:52.326 A:middle
as collections are
concerned is that collections

00:08:52.426 --> 00:08:56.656 A:middle
in the Photos Framework
runtime don't actually cache

00:08:56.656 --> 00:08:57.486 A:middle
their contents.

00:08:57.486 --> 00:08:57.916 A:middle
[ Cough ]

00:08:57.916 --> 00:08:59.526 A:middle
Excuse me.

00:08:59.796 --> 00:09:03.016 A:middle
So what that means is that
in order to find the assets


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.796 --> 00:09:03.016 A:middle
So what that means is that
in order to find the assets

00:09:03.016 --> 00:09:06.266 A:middle
that live in an album you need
to perform a fetch similar

00:09:06.266 --> 00:09:08.916 A:middle
to the ones that we just saw
for general purpose fetching.

00:09:09.486 --> 00:09:10.886 A:middle
So here's an illustration
of that.

00:09:11.246 --> 00:09:13.656 A:middle
To fetch the assets in an
Asset Collection represented

00:09:13.656 --> 00:09:17.786 A:middle
by an album, we're getting back
assets, so we use a class method

00:09:17.786 --> 00:09:19.586 A:middle
on the PHAsset class

00:09:20.066 --> 00:09:22.776 A:middle
and fetchAssetsInAsset
Collection:myAlbum.

00:09:23.356 --> 00:09:27.526 A:middle
Now the next construct
that I want

00:09:27.526 --> 00:09:31.406 A:middle
to cover here is something we
call a Transient Collection.

00:09:31.406 --> 00:09:36.376 A:middle
And this is a really useful
construct that we've made a lot

00:09:36.376 --> 00:09:40.146 A:middle
of use of in the photos
application where we wanted

00:09:40.146 --> 00:09:43.636 A:middle
to represent a collection
that isn't represented

00:09:43.636 --> 00:09:45.146 A:middle
in the actual photo library.

00:09:45.556 --> 00:09:49.316 A:middle
An example of that is a search
result or a user selection

00:09:49.316 --> 00:09:51.266 A:middle
as they're picking
off items in the UI.

00:09:52.196 --> 00:09:57.966 A:middle
And by taking that selection
of items or model objects

00:09:57.966 --> 00:09:59.816 A:middle
and putting it into a
Transient Collection,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:00.166 --> 00:10:04.926 A:middle
the benefit is the Transient
Collection is interchangeable

00:10:04.986 --> 00:10:07.146 A:middle
with the regular collections
that you might fetch

00:10:07.146 --> 00:10:07.976 A:middle
out of the photo library.

00:10:08.976 --> 00:10:12.376 A:middle
So you can do things like reuse
your existing view controllers

00:10:12.436 --> 00:10:14.846 A:middle
or fetch the contents of
a Transient Collection

00:10:15.116 --> 00:10:17.496 A:middle
without worrying about whether
it's represented by something

00:10:17.496 --> 00:10:20.186 A:middle
that really exists
on the photo library

00:10:20.436 --> 00:10:21.306 A:middle
or if it's just something

00:10:21.306 --> 00:10:23.106 A:middle
that your user is working
with in the runtime.

00:10:23.496 --> 00:10:27.726 A:middle
To create a Transient Collection
there's a class method

00:10:27.726 --> 00:10:29.236 A:middle
on the Asset Collection class

00:10:29.236 --> 00:10:30.896 A:middle
to create a Transient
Asset Collection.

00:10:30.956 --> 00:10:33.066 A:middle
You could also create a
Transient Collection list.

00:10:33.606 --> 00:10:35.576 A:middle
But to create a Transient
Asset Collection we call

00:10:35.576 --> 00:10:38.806 A:middle
transientAssetCollection
WithAssets and simply pass

00:10:38.806 --> 00:10:41.746 A:middle
in an array of assets as
well as an optional title.

00:10:44.946 --> 00:10:48.526 A:middle
So what are you getting back
when you perform these fetches?

00:10:48.946 --> 00:10:51.386 A:middle
Most of the time when you're
writing an application to work

00:10:51.386 --> 00:10:53.846 A:middle
with photos, you're going
to be reading those objects,

00:10:54.366 --> 00:10:56.076 A:middle
looking through them,
working with them.

00:10:56.266 --> 00:10:58.266 A:middle
So we wanted to make it
as simple as possible

00:10:58.266 --> 00:11:00.696 A:middle
to get those objects out and
to work with them directly.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:58.266 --> 00:11:00.696 A:middle
to get those objects out and
to work with them directly.

00:11:01.016 --> 00:11:03.016 A:middle
So you wanted to get
synchronous results

00:11:03.016 --> 00:11:04.086 A:middle
and you want them quickly.

00:11:05.866 --> 00:11:09.056 A:middle
But, especially when you think
about iCloud Photo Library,

00:11:09.176 --> 00:11:12.996 A:middle
the results of the fetch could
be potentially very large,

00:11:13.256 --> 00:11:15.536 A:middle
in the tens of thousands
of assets or even more.

00:11:16.516 --> 00:11:17.886 A:middle
So it's really important

00:11:17.886 --> 00:11:20.316 A:middle
that you don't fetch all those
objects into memory at once.

00:11:20.976 --> 00:11:23.466 A:middle
And you really want to
work with them in batches

00:11:23.466 --> 00:11:25.956 A:middle
as you're working with them
or displaying them on screen.

00:11:27.166 --> 00:11:29.166 A:middle
But we didn't want to put
that complexity on you.

00:11:30.186 --> 00:11:33.486 A:middle
So what we did is we've
introduced a class

00:11:33.486 --> 00:11:35.266 A:middle
to represent the
objects that you get back

00:11:35.266 --> 00:11:37.466 A:middle
from a fetch called
a PHFetchResult.

00:11:38.606 --> 00:11:43.296 A:middle
And the PHFetchResult takes care
of tracking the full results set

00:11:43.586 --> 00:11:44.316 A:middle
by keeping track

00:11:44.316 --> 00:11:46.856 A:middle
of the lightweight
IDs representing each

00:11:46.856 --> 00:11:48.536 A:middle
of the contents of that fetch.

00:11:48.986 --> 00:11:52.776 A:middle
But when you access the contents
of that fetch result to pull one

00:11:52.776 --> 00:11:55.776 A:middle
of the objects out, we'll vend
you a fully realized object

00:11:56.086 --> 00:11:56.896 A:middle
that you can work with.

00:11:57.896 --> 00:12:00.906 A:middle
It's got an API that's familiar
and similar to the NSArray


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:57.896 --> 00:12:00.906 A:middle
It's got an API that's familiar
and similar to the NSArray

00:12:00.906 --> 00:12:03.406 A:middle
so it should be easy
to work with.

00:12:03.806 --> 00:12:07.896 A:middle
And I'd like to show you
an example of what it looks

00:12:07.896 --> 00:12:10.426 A:middle
like as you're working
with a fetch result.

00:12:11.406 --> 00:12:16.146 A:middle
So on the slide here I've
shown a fetch result that's

00:12:16.146 --> 00:12:18.416 A:middle
representing, say, a
fetch of 10,000 assets

00:12:19.096 --> 00:12:21.706 A:middle
and as we're iterating
through that result set,

00:12:21.706 --> 00:12:26.666 A:middle
pulling out assets, as we
access one of the indexes,

00:12:27.076 --> 00:12:29.916 A:middle
we'll behind the scenes pull
in a full batch to represent

00:12:29.916 --> 00:12:32.026 A:middle
that object as well
as many of the others.

00:12:32.816 --> 00:12:36.696 A:middle
And as you iterate through over
that batch to the next batch,

00:12:36.876 --> 00:12:38.976 A:middle
we'll pull in the
next batch of objects

00:12:39.246 --> 00:12:42.346 A:middle
but release the previous ones
so you don't wind up holding

00:12:42.346 --> 00:12:43.266 A:middle
onto all that in memory.

00:12:45.326 --> 00:12:48.806 A:middle
So now that you've got the
[applause] - ah, thanks.

00:12:51.076 --> 00:12:53.656 A:middle
Now that you've got model
objects that you're working

00:12:53.656 --> 00:12:58.736 A:middle
with in your application, your
user may, will, oftentimes want

00:12:58.736 --> 00:13:00.206 A:middle
to make changes to
those objects.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:12:58.736 --> 00:13:00.206 A:middle
to make changes to
those objects.

00:13:00.706 --> 00:13:03.786 A:middle
So I want to take a look at
how you can make model changes

00:13:04.426 --> 00:13:07.176 A:middle
with those model
objects to support things

00:13:07.176 --> 00:13:11.516 A:middle
like the user wanting to
favorite a photo or add a photo

00:13:11.516 --> 00:13:15.056 A:middle
to an album because,
as I said earlier,

00:13:15.376 --> 00:13:17.156 A:middle
the model objects
themselves are read-only

00:13:17.156 --> 00:13:18.666 A:middle
so you can't mutate
them directly.

00:13:20.416 --> 00:13:22.786 A:middle
So the way we express changes is

00:13:22.786 --> 00:13:25.346 A:middle
through a Change
Request API that's based

00:13:25.346 --> 00:13:30.056 A:middle
on change request
classes that you create

00:13:30.056 --> 00:13:33.376 A:middle
in a change request block and
then hand to the photo library

00:13:34.056 --> 00:13:36.736 A:middle
so that it can apply those
changes asynchronously

00:13:36.896 --> 00:13:37.856 A:middle
out of process.

00:13:38.666 --> 00:13:41.196 A:middle
And the reasons those changes
are applied out of process

00:13:41.356 --> 00:13:43.286 A:middle
and asynchronously is twofold.

00:13:44.096 --> 00:13:47.556 A:middle
The first reason is,
for some operations,

00:13:47.736 --> 00:13:51.516 A:middle
it may be very expensive
or processor-intensive

00:13:51.516 --> 00:13:52.736 A:middle
or just take a long time.

00:13:53.346 --> 00:13:56.296 A:middle
But even more importantly than
that, because you're working

00:13:56.296 --> 00:13:58.346 A:middle
with the user's actual
photo library,

00:13:58.756 --> 00:14:02.406 A:middle
some of those actions may
require user authentication.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:58.756 --> 00:14:02.406 A:middle
some of those actions may
require user authentication.

00:14:02.736 --> 00:14:05.066 A:middle
For example, if you
wanted to delete 10 photos,

00:14:06.276 --> 00:14:08.626 A:middle
the photo library's going
to prompt the user to say,

00:14:09.086 --> 00:14:13.406 A:middle
"Is this application allowed
to delete these 10 photos?"

00:14:13.666 --> 00:14:17.636 A:middle
to allow the user to have
a chance to confirm that.

00:14:19.406 --> 00:14:21.426 A:middle
So let's take a look at
the change request classes.

00:14:21.426 --> 00:14:22.796 A:middle
It's actually pretty simple.

00:14:22.796 --> 00:14:26.416 A:middle
For each model object class,
there is a change request class.

00:14:26.416 --> 00:14:28.036 A:middle
We've got the
AssetChangeRequest,

00:14:28.036 --> 00:14:29.466 A:middle
the
AssetCollectionChangeRequest,

00:14:29.816 --> 00:14:32.016 A:middle
and the
CollectionListChangeRequest.

00:14:32.666 --> 00:14:35.796 A:middle
And each of these change
request classes provide model

00:14:35.796 --> 00:14:38.966 A:middle
object-specific APIs to allow
you to perform the types

00:14:38.966 --> 00:14:40.116 A:middle
of changes that they allow.

00:14:41.256 --> 00:14:45.716 A:middle
So the example I'm showing here
is for the asset change request

00:14:45.716 --> 00:14:48.126 A:middle
where you can set the
creation date for an asset

00:14:48.436 --> 00:14:49.646 A:middle
or to set it as a favorite.

00:14:53.666 --> 00:14:55.936 A:middle
Some other things to understand

00:14:55.936 --> 00:14:57.356 A:middle
about the change
request classes is

00:14:57.356 --> 00:15:00.556 A:middle
that they are not subclasses
of the model classes.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:57.356 --> 00:15:00.556 A:middle
that they are not subclasses
of the model classes.

00:15:00.556 --> 00:15:02.396 A:middle
And there's a good
reason for that.

00:15:02.626 --> 00:15:05.016 A:middle
We wanted to provide a
really clear separation

00:15:05.016 --> 00:15:08.436 A:middle
between the thread-safe,
immutable model objects

00:15:08.566 --> 00:15:10.496 A:middle
and the objects that
express mutations.

00:15:10.796 --> 00:15:12.266 A:middle
That's the change
request classes.

00:15:13.056 --> 00:15:15.726 A:middle
These change request classes
are also only valid to work

00:15:15.726 --> 00:15:17.616 A:middle
within a change request block.

00:15:18.086 --> 00:15:22.546 A:middle
So I'd like to illustrate
that with an example now.

00:15:23.086 --> 00:15:29.436 A:middle
So here's an example where I've
provided a sample implementation

00:15:29.436 --> 00:15:33.856 A:middle
of a method to toggle whether
an asset has been marked

00:15:33.856 --> 00:15:34.436 A:middle
as a favorite.

00:15:35.586 --> 00:15:37.226 A:middle
So the first thing we'll do

00:15:37.226 --> 00:15:41.526 A:middle
in this method is ask
the shared photo library

00:15:41.526 --> 00:15:43.776 A:middle
to perform some changes,
and we'll pass

00:15:43.776 --> 00:15:45.276 A:middle
in a change request block here.

00:15:47.776 --> 00:15:51.336 A:middle
First step in that block is
to create a change request

00:15:51.336 --> 00:15:53.516 A:middle
for the asset that we were
provided in the method.

00:15:54.246 --> 00:15:57.026 A:middle
And we're using the
PHAssetChangeRequest class here

00:15:57.026 --> 00:15:57.556 A:middle
you can see.

00:15:58.126 --> 00:16:03.236 A:middle
And then the last
step is simply to set


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:58.126 --> 00:16:03.236 A:middle
And then the last
step is simply to set

00:16:03.846 --> 00:16:08.466 A:middle
on the change request the value
of Favorite to the inverse value

00:16:08.466 --> 00:16:11.036 A:middle
of what the asset currently has.

00:16:12.346 --> 00:16:16.446 A:middle
That's enough for the block to
get passed to the photo library

00:16:16.836 --> 00:16:19.366 A:middle
and those changes to be
performed on your behalf.

00:16:20.936 --> 00:16:23.626 A:middle
After those changes are
performed we'll call back the

00:16:23.626 --> 00:16:28.206 A:middle
completion handler and let
you know if it was successful

00:16:28.546 --> 00:16:29.756 A:middle
in performing those changes.

00:16:33.416 --> 00:16:36.296 A:middle
So one other aspect of
working with change requests

00:16:36.296 --> 00:16:40.276 A:middle
that you'll want to do is
to create new model objects.

00:16:40.726 --> 00:16:42.526 A:middle
And you can create
new model objects

00:16:42.606 --> 00:16:44.466 A:middle
with these same change
request classes

00:16:44.696 --> 00:16:45.866 A:middle
but creating a different kind

00:16:45.866 --> 00:16:49.056 A:middle
of change request using
a creation request.

00:16:49.196 --> 00:16:50.886 A:middle
So in this case I've
shown as an example

00:16:50.886 --> 00:16:53.106 A:middle
where you can create a new asset

00:16:53.106 --> 00:16:56.966 A:middle
from an image using the
creationRequestForAssetFromImage

00:16:57.256 --> 00:16:57.946 A:middle
class method.

00:16:59.246 --> 00:17:02.316 A:middle
And if all you want to
do is create a new asset


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:59.246 --> 00:17:02.316 A:middle
And if all you want to
do is create a new asset

00:17:02.316 --> 00:17:04.955 A:middle
from an image, you're done.

00:17:04.955 --> 00:17:08.156 A:middle
You just make this call
within a change request block

00:17:08.156 --> 00:17:10.406 A:middle
and the library will take
care of adding the asset.

00:17:11.506 --> 00:17:13.996 A:middle
But if you want to
work with that asset

00:17:14.165 --> 00:17:17.896 A:middle
within that change request block
to do some additional work, say,

00:17:17.896 --> 00:17:21.455 A:middle
to add it to an album, well,

00:17:21.455 --> 00:17:24.566 A:middle
remember that the asset
won't actually be created

00:17:24.566 --> 00:17:26.665 A:middle
until the work is
performed out of process.

00:17:27.306 --> 00:17:32.566 A:middle
So within the same change
request block you can access a

00:17:32.566 --> 00:17:35.736 A:middle
placeholder object from the
change request representing

00:17:35.736 --> 00:17:37.286 A:middle
that new unsaved object.

00:17:37.616 --> 00:17:40.986 A:middle
And then you can use that
placeholder to add the new asset

00:17:40.986 --> 00:17:45.396 A:middle
to a collection or even
potentially a new placeholder

00:17:45.396 --> 00:17:46.166 A:middle
for a collection.

00:17:48.076 --> 00:17:49.306 A:middle
One other thing you can get

00:17:49.306 --> 00:17:52.836 A:middle
from a placeholder object is you
can access the localIdentifier

00:17:52.836 --> 00:17:55.886 A:middle
which is a unique string
that you can use later

00:17:55.886 --> 00:17:58.766 A:middle
in your application to
fetch that object back even

00:17:58.766 --> 00:17:59.886 A:middle
on another invocation.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:01.736 --> 00:18:04.096 A:middle
So what happens to
these changes?

00:18:05.766 --> 00:18:07.446 A:middle
Well, the changes are done

00:18:07.446 --> 00:18:09.106 A:middle
when the completion
handler is invoked.

00:18:10.016 --> 00:18:12.466 A:middle
But the model objects
are read-only

00:18:12.466 --> 00:18:14.806 A:middle
and they aren't automatically
refreshed or modified

00:18:14.806 --> 00:18:15.776 A:middle
out from underneath you.

00:18:16.636 --> 00:18:19.336 A:middle
But more important than these
two things when we're talking

00:18:19.336 --> 00:18:22.466 A:middle
about changes, there's a really
important thing to understand.

00:18:23.536 --> 00:18:26.906 A:middle
The changes that you requested
may incur side effects

00:18:27.636 --> 00:18:31.406 A:middle
or may be influenced by
external changes coming

00:18:31.406 --> 00:18:32.126 A:middle
in from elsewhere.

00:18:33.106 --> 00:18:35.766 A:middle
In fact, there are a lot
of sources for change

00:18:35.766 --> 00:18:36.946 A:middle
into the photo library.

00:18:37.216 --> 00:18:38.526 A:middle
There's your application.

00:18:38.626 --> 00:18:40.066 A:middle
There's the built-in
application.

00:18:40.376 --> 00:18:41.766 A:middle
There's iCloud Photo Library,

00:18:42.036 --> 00:18:44.416 A:middle
Cloud Photo Sharing
and my Photo Stream.

00:18:44.926 --> 00:18:47.366 A:middle
And all of these things can
have an impact on the data

00:18:47.366 --> 00:18:48.176 A:middle
that you're working with.

00:18:48.926 --> 00:18:51.816 A:middle
So what we recommend is
that, instead of trying

00:18:51.816 --> 00:18:54.676 A:middle
to take the result of a change
in your completion handler,

00:18:55.316 --> 00:18:58.406 A:middle
you work with a single
change notification system

00:18:58.656 --> 00:19:00.566 A:middle
to handle changes
there and reflect them


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:58.656 --> 00:19:00.566 A:middle
to handle changes
there and reflect them

00:19:00.566 --> 00:19:03.606 A:middle
to your user that way.

00:19:03.796 --> 00:19:06.556 A:middle
So what happens is,
anytime there is a change

00:19:06.556 --> 00:19:09.646 A:middle
to the photo library,
we'll publish a PHChange

00:19:09.686 --> 00:19:11.556 A:middle
to registered observers.

00:19:12.616 --> 00:19:14.866 A:middle
And that change is delivered
on a background queue

00:19:15.296 --> 00:19:18.596 A:middle
and it provides details on
updated and deleted objects.

00:19:19.236 --> 00:19:22.276 A:middle
But where it begins to
get really powerful is

00:19:22.276 --> 00:19:23.866 A:middle
when you're working
with fetch results,

00:19:24.716 --> 00:19:27.566 A:middle
where it can provide you
details on what indexes

00:19:27.566 --> 00:19:30.426 A:middle
and objects were inserted,
updated, deleted or moved

00:19:30.726 --> 00:19:32.216 A:middle
that apply to that fetch result.

00:19:33.516 --> 00:19:34.766 A:middle
And I want to dig
a little deeper

00:19:34.766 --> 00:19:36.976 A:middle
into the fetch result
change details.

00:19:38.026 --> 00:19:40.476 A:middle
When you create a fetch
result by performing a fetch

00:19:40.476 --> 00:19:42.726 A:middle
for a collection or any
other general-purpose fetch,

00:19:43.396 --> 00:19:45.906 A:middle
the fetch result will
implicitly register itself

00:19:46.146 --> 00:19:48.936 A:middle
with the photo library
for calculating changes.

00:19:49.816 --> 00:19:53.576 A:middle
And all those changed details
are calculated in the background

00:19:53.816 --> 00:19:57.066 A:middle
so they don't run while
your user is interacting

00:19:57.066 --> 00:19:57.926 A:middle
with your application.

00:19:59.816 --> 00:20:03.456 A:middle
If you're fetching a fetch
result and you're not interested


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:19:59.816 --> 00:20:03.456 A:middle
If you're fetching a fetch
result and you're not interested

00:20:03.516 --> 00:20:05.486 A:middle
in change details, you can opt

00:20:05.486 --> 00:20:08.796 A:middle
out of the difference
calculation via one

00:20:08.796 --> 00:20:09.726 A:middle
of those fetch options.

00:20:10.266 --> 00:20:13.296 A:middle
But if you do want the details,

00:20:13.296 --> 00:20:18.046 A:middle
if you want those incremental
differences, then it's important

00:20:18.046 --> 00:20:21.636 A:middle
that you get the updated fetch
result for the fetch result

00:20:21.636 --> 00:20:26.746 A:middle
that you started with from
the PHFetchResultChangeDetails

00:20:26.746 --> 00:20:27.336 A:middle
object.

00:20:27.956 --> 00:20:29.626 A:middle
And I'm going to walk
you through an example

00:20:29.626 --> 00:20:31.816 A:middle
to demonstrate why
that's so important.

00:20:32.186 --> 00:20:36.166 A:middle
When the photo library
receives a change,

00:20:36.726 --> 00:20:39.016 A:middle
if you've registered
yourself as an observer,

00:20:39.316 --> 00:20:41.396 A:middle
we'll call the
PhotoLibraryDidChange method

00:20:41.396 --> 00:20:43.376 A:middle
and pass you the
PHChange instance.

00:20:43.916 --> 00:20:48.326 A:middle
In this case, in this
example, which by the way,

00:20:48.326 --> 00:20:50.896 A:middle
this example is taken from the
sample code that's provided

00:20:50.896 --> 00:20:53.996 A:middle
with this session, so I've
omitted some of the details

00:20:53.996 --> 00:20:55.796 A:middle
to make it a little
clearer on stage,

00:20:56.236 --> 00:20:58.666 A:middle
but all of this is
available in the sample code

00:20:58.666 --> 00:21:02.336 A:middle
that you can download
from the WWDC website.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:20:58.666 --> 00:21:02.336 A:middle
that you can download
from the WWDC website.

00:21:03.476 --> 00:21:05.646 A:middle
Anyway, getting back to that.

00:21:06.436 --> 00:21:08.086 A:middle
The first thing we're
going to want to do

00:21:08.086 --> 00:21:12.816 A:middle
in our change handler here is
to dispatch to the main queue.

00:21:12.816 --> 00:21:14.966 A:middle
And the reason for that is
because we're going to work

00:21:14.966 --> 00:21:17.796 A:middle
with our user interface
objects, our view controllers,

00:21:18.086 --> 00:21:20.976 A:middle
and you know it's only safe to
access those on the main queue.

00:21:22.556 --> 00:21:24.576 A:middle
So once we've dispatched

00:21:24.576 --> 00:21:27.316 A:middle
to the main queue we'll
ask the change instance,

00:21:28.276 --> 00:21:30.826 A:middle
"Were there any changed
details for the fetch result

00:21:30.826 --> 00:21:32.886 A:middle
that we are working with
in our view controller?"

00:21:32.886 --> 00:21:36.496 A:middle
And in this case, we've got -
I've represented self.assets.

00:21:36.496 --> 00:21:41.646 A:middle
That's a fetch result that we're
presenting in a collection view.

00:21:42.726 --> 00:21:46.056 A:middle
So if there's a change that
affects the collection view,

00:21:46.056 --> 00:21:47.336 A:middle
the contents of that
collection view,

00:21:47.446 --> 00:21:48.876 A:middle
we want to know what
those details are.

00:21:48.876 --> 00:21:51.226 A:middle
So we'll ask the change instance
for those change details.

00:21:51.746 --> 00:21:55.666 A:middle
And if there were any change
details then we know we need

00:21:55.666 --> 00:22:00.196 A:middle
to update our fetch result based
on what those changes were.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:21:55.666 --> 00:22:00.196 A:middle
to update our fetch result based
on what those changes were.

00:22:00.536 --> 00:22:02.346 A:middle
And the way to get
those details,

00:22:02.346 --> 00:22:04.656 A:middle
or to get that updated fetch
result as I was saying,

00:22:04.916 --> 00:22:07.806 A:middle
is to get it directly from
the change details object.

00:22:08.666 --> 00:22:10.826 A:middle
The change details have
already done that work for us,

00:22:11.016 --> 00:22:13.856 A:middle
and that way we're sure that the
other details we're going to ask

00:22:13.856 --> 00:22:16.096 A:middle
for about inserts, updates
and deletes are going

00:22:16.096 --> 00:22:19.166 A:middle
to exactly match up to the new
result that we're working with.

00:22:20.376 --> 00:22:21.966 A:middle
So on the second slide here,

00:22:22.476 --> 00:22:26.056 A:middle
I'm going to show you how
nicely this works with an object

00:22:26.056 --> 00:22:26.996 A:middle
like the collectionView.

00:22:27.786 --> 00:22:29.446 A:middle
So now we can tell
the collectionView

00:22:29.946 --> 00:22:32.716 A:middle
to perform a batch
of updates and walk

00:22:32.716 --> 00:22:36.376 A:middle
through the changed details to
see where there removed indexes?

00:22:36.596 --> 00:22:39.016 A:middle
If there were, we'll
translate them into index paths

00:22:39.016 --> 00:22:41.256 A:middle
that the collectionView
can understand and tell it

00:22:41.256 --> 00:22:44.796 A:middle
to delete the items
at those paths.

00:22:44.966 --> 00:22:46.986 A:middle
Similarly, we'll ask
the change details,

00:22:46.986 --> 00:22:49.186 A:middle
were there inserted indexes
in that fetch result?

00:22:49.806 --> 00:22:51.936 A:middle
If there were, we'll tell
the collectionView again

00:22:52.296 --> 00:22:55.546 A:middle
to insert items at those paths.

