And to tell you about how
to do that, Simon Bovet.

00:43:11.516 --> 00:43:16.736 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:43:17.236 --> 00:43:18.656 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:43:18.876 --> 00:43:20.376 A:middle
My name is Simon Bovet.

00:43:20.376 --> 00:43:22.616 A:middle
And in this last
part of the session,

00:43:22.966 --> 00:43:24.876 A:middle
let's talk about Photo
Editing Extensions.

00:43:26.326 --> 00:43:28.206 A:middle
So what are Photo
Editing Extensions?

00:43:28.676 --> 00:43:30.626 A:middle
How can they be useful
to you developers?

00:43:31.086 --> 00:43:32.716 A:middle
And what do they
bring to our users?

00:43:32.796 --> 00:43:39.856 A:middle
So it's a new feature in iOS 8
that allows the users to access

00:43:39.966 --> 00:43:44.846 A:middle
to your Image or Video
Editing tool right

00:43:44.846 --> 00:43:49.076 A:middle
from within the built-in
camera or photo applications.

00:43:50.486 --> 00:43:52.856 A:middle
No need for the user to
switch between applications.

00:43:53.136 --> 00:43:56.036 A:middle
No need for the user to
grant specific access rights

00:43:56.036 --> 00:43:56.876 A:middle
to your application.

00:43:57.206 --> 00:44:01.696 A:middle
It's a very simple way for your
tool to reach its audience.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:43:57.206 --> 00:44:01.696 A:middle
It's a very simple way for your
tool to reach its audience.

00:44:02.226 --> 00:44:03.606 A:middle
And we think it's a great way

00:44:03.836 --> 00:44:07.096 A:middle
to put your creativity inside
the hands of our users.

00:44:08.086 --> 00:44:11.326 A:middle
So this feature has been shown
in the Keynote on Monday,

00:44:11.326 --> 00:44:13.356 A:middle
but let me refresh your
memories with a few slides.

00:44:14.256 --> 00:44:20.346 A:middle
So here we are on iPhone editing
an image using the iOS 8's

00:44:20.446 --> 00:44:22.036 A:middle
built-in Photos application.

00:44:22.996 --> 00:44:25.966 A:middle
The user can tap on
the top left button

00:44:26.796 --> 00:44:29.576 A:middle
and access any available
editing extension.

00:44:30.596 --> 00:44:31.266 A:middle
Can pick one.

00:44:31.946 --> 00:44:37.326 A:middle
And this could be your Editing
tool extending the reading

00:44:37.326 --> 00:44:39.056 A:middle
capabilities of the
built-in apps.

00:44:39.876 --> 00:44:41.326 A:middle
So now the user can interact

00:44:41.326 --> 00:44:43.036 A:middle
with whatever interface
you want to provide.

00:44:43.676 --> 00:44:47.796 A:middle
And when the user is done,
the changes are saved right

00:44:47.796 --> 00:44:50.156 A:middle
in place inside the
user's photo library.

00:44:50.626 --> 00:44:52.686 A:middle
No need to create the
duplicated assets.

00:44:53.506 --> 00:44:56.276 A:middle
And if the user has turned
on iCloud Photo Library,

00:44:56.916 --> 00:44:59.986 A:middle
those changes will be
applied to all of the devices.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:45:00.436 --> 00:45:01.766 A:middle
So the user could go on his iPad

00:45:01.766 --> 00:45:04.896 A:middle
and then draw your beautiful
effects on a larger screen.

00:45:06.036 --> 00:45:09.386 A:middle
So, what do you need to
create your own photo

00:45:09.386 --> 00:45:10.426 A:middle
editing extension?

00:45:11.576 --> 00:45:13.426 A:middle
And it turns out that
it's really simple.

00:45:13.926 --> 00:45:15.236 A:middle
It's basically three steps.

00:45:15.916 --> 00:45:18.606 A:middle
The first one is to create
an app extension target.

00:45:19.896 --> 00:45:22.016 A:middle
The second one is to
provide a view controller

00:45:22.336 --> 00:45:24.556 A:middle
which will manage the
UI of your extension.

00:45:25.406 --> 00:45:27.286 A:middle
And then this view
controller needs

00:45:27.286 --> 00:45:31.216 A:middle
to adopt a specific protocol
which is a set of methods

00:45:31.736 --> 00:45:33.546 A:middle
that Photos will call in order

00:45:33.546 --> 00:45:34.926 A:middle
to communicate with
your extension.

00:45:35.456 --> 00:45:41.966 A:middle
The good news is the first two
steps are really easy thanks

00:45:41.966 --> 00:45:42.886 A:middle
to the new Xcode.

00:45:44.186 --> 00:45:46.196 A:middle
Basically all that
you need to do is,

00:45:46.196 --> 00:45:49.856 A:middle
from your application's Xcode
project, add a new target

00:45:50.846 --> 00:45:53.506 A:middle
and select the Photo
Editing Extension template.

00:45:54.496 --> 00:45:57.736 A:middle
Xcode will create whatever is
necessary for you go get started

00:45:58.156 --> 00:45:59.306 A:middle
and have something working.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:46:00.406 --> 00:46:04.026 A:middle
It will create a view controller
which you can start using

00:46:04.836 --> 00:46:07.266 A:middle
or which you can replace
with your own if you happen

00:46:07.266 --> 00:46:10.026 A:middle
to have your existing
tool or view controller

00:46:10.026 --> 00:46:10.926 A:middle
that you want to reuse.

00:46:11.456 --> 00:46:13.196 A:middle
A note about the user interface.

00:46:14.506 --> 00:46:16.866 A:middle
You've seen photo extensions
are shown fullscreen.

00:46:17.746 --> 00:46:21.116 A:middle
Now on the top bar, with the
Cancel and Done buttons as well

00:46:21.116 --> 00:46:23.666 A:middle
as the title of your
application,

00:46:24.046 --> 00:46:26.396 A:middle
it's shown automatically
for you by the Photos app.

00:46:27.646 --> 00:46:30.636 A:middle
So if you, say, you'd like
to design your extension not

00:46:30.636 --> 00:46:32.076 A:middle
to have its own navigation bar.

00:46:34.886 --> 00:46:38.096 A:middle
Now onto the protocol
adoption, so the protocol

00:46:38.096 --> 00:46:39.946 A:middle
which is specific
to photo extensions.

00:46:41.186 --> 00:46:44.276 A:middle
And this protocol is defining
the photo's UIFramework

00:46:44.926 --> 00:46:47.426 A:middle
and is the
PHContentEditingController.

00:46:48.276 --> 00:46:49.696 A:middle
It consists of four methods.

00:46:50.336 --> 00:46:53.536 A:middle
And the first one,
quite obviously,

00:46:54.116 --> 00:46:57.066 A:middle
is called when the user
selects your extension.

00:46:57.796 --> 00:47:02.056 A:middle
And this where you get the input
data before your extension is


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:46:57.796 --> 00:47:02.056 A:middle
And this where you get the input
data before your extension is

00:47:02.056 --> 00:47:02.986 A:middle
presented onscreen.

00:47:03.626 --> 00:47:09.446 A:middle
A simple implementation
could look like this.

00:47:09.656 --> 00:47:12.966 A:middle
And the first thing you might
notice is that the input object

00:47:12.966 --> 00:47:15.586 A:middle
which is given to you,
the PHContentEditingInput,

00:47:15.646 --> 00:47:17.686 A:middle
is exactly the same object

00:47:17.936 --> 00:47:20.496 A:middle
as the one Karl described
just a few minutes ago.

00:47:21.086 --> 00:47:23.286 A:middle
So, basically, we have
the exact same classes,

00:47:23.286 --> 00:47:26.746 A:middle
the exact same concepts, as
when editing a photo using the

00:47:26.746 --> 00:47:29.986 A:middle
photo's framework just here
wrapped slightly differently

00:47:29.986 --> 00:47:31.776 A:middle
for the specific
needs of an extension.

00:47:33.116 --> 00:47:37.256 A:middle
So, you would typically
read out the input image.

00:47:37.676 --> 00:47:39.236 A:middle
In this particular case
we're going to work

00:47:39.236 --> 00:47:40.876 A:middle
with a display-size
representation.

00:47:41.116 --> 00:47:43.146 A:middle
We don't need the full-size
image right away here.

00:47:43.836 --> 00:47:46.716 A:middle
Then we're going to decode
any input.adjustmentData

00:47:47.226 --> 00:47:50.076 A:middle
or fall back to some default
settings if there's none.

00:47:51.156 --> 00:47:55.526 A:middle
Then you set up your user
interface the way you need it.

00:47:55.526 --> 00:47:57.486 A:middle
And you typically find
it's useful to hold

00:47:57.486 --> 00:47:59.566 A:middle
on to the input object
that was given to you.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:48:00.316 --> 00:48:03.396 A:middle
Now the user will interact
with your extension.

00:48:03.626 --> 00:48:06.846 A:middle
And when the user is done, the
second method will be called.

00:48:07.616 --> 00:48:09.386 A:middle
And this is when your extension,

00:48:09.746 --> 00:48:13.796 A:middle
we need to provide the final
output data and hand it back.

00:48:15.126 --> 00:48:17.406 A:middle
Second implementation
can look like this.

00:48:18.286 --> 00:48:20.976 A:middle
For images, you drag
a JPEG representation

00:48:20.976 --> 00:48:23.706 A:middle
of the full-size image with
your effects applied to it.

00:48:24.396 --> 00:48:26.466 A:middle
You still create this
adjustment's data object

00:48:26.466 --> 00:48:30.026 A:middle
which describe whatever you've
applied to the input image.

00:48:30.716 --> 00:48:32.266 A:middle
And then you create
an output object

00:48:32.266 --> 00:48:34.026 A:middle
that wraps all this information.

00:48:34.506 --> 00:48:36.676 A:middle
And when you're done, you
call the completionHandler.

00:48:39.036 --> 00:48:42.736 A:middle
You notice in this example
that the flow is synchronous,

00:48:42.996 --> 00:48:43.856 A:middle
but it doesn't have to be.

00:48:44.256 --> 00:48:46.196 A:middle
If you prefer to have an
asynchronous workflow,

00:48:46.196 --> 00:48:46.946 A:middle
it's totally fine.

00:48:47.226 --> 00:48:49.156 A:middle
You just have to call
the completionHandler

00:48:49.546 --> 00:48:50.946 A:middle
when your output is ready.

00:48:55.296 --> 00:48:59.206 A:middle
Now you remember the story
about resuming editing.

00:48:59.496 --> 00:49:03.736 A:middle
So we imagine that the user
selects your extension using an


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:48:59.496 --> 00:49:03.736 A:middle
So we imagine that the user
selects your extension using an

00:49:03.736 --> 00:49:06.086 A:middle
image or a video that
already has been edited

00:49:06.086 --> 00:49:07.696 A:middle
and that has some
adjustments data.

00:49:08.766 --> 00:49:11.766 A:middle
You remember the first
question that we asked you is,

00:49:12.106 --> 00:49:16.206 A:middle
do you understand that given the
existing adjustment data on it,

00:49:16.206 --> 00:49:18.996 A:middle
and that way we can provide
you with the appropriate input.

00:49:19.596 --> 00:49:26.356 A:middle
And this is when this method can
handle adjustments data is going

00:49:26.356 --> 00:49:28.016 A:middle
to get called a new extension.

00:49:28.576 --> 00:49:32.706 A:middle
And, typically, implementation
could be as simple

00:49:32.706 --> 00:49:36.926 A:middle
as checking whether you support
the formatIdentifier and version

00:49:36.926 --> 00:49:38.956 A:middle
of this adjustment data.

00:49:38.956 --> 00:49:42.596 A:middle
And, finally, the last
method pretty obviously is

00:49:42.596 --> 00:49:45.056 A:middle
when the user cancels
your extension.

00:49:45.936 --> 00:49:47.766 A:middle
One thing to notice,
which isn't obvious,

00:49:47.766 --> 00:49:50.126 A:middle
is that this method can
be called at any time.

00:49:50.906 --> 00:49:53.616 A:middle
So, for example, if your
extension requires some time

00:49:53.616 --> 00:49:55.476 A:middle
to produce the output
- for example,

00:49:55.476 --> 00:49:58.786 A:middle
you're editing a video
- the user could decide

00:49:58.786 --> 00:50:00.976 A:middle
to interrupt you and cancel
right away at any time.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:49:58.786 --> 00:50:00.976 A:middle
to interrupt you and cancel
right away at any time.

00:50:01.046 --> 00:50:05.996 A:middle
So just keep that in mind.

00:50:06.146 --> 00:50:09.196 A:middle
And this is basically
all what you need

00:50:09.556 --> 00:50:11.646 A:middle
to create your own
photo editing extension.

00:50:12.126 --> 00:50:15.796 A:middle
So we are really excited to see
all the tools that you are going

00:50:15.796 --> 00:50:17.936 A:middle
to create and all the great
ideas that you are going

00:50:17.936 --> 00:50:20.336 A:middle
to provide to our
users using this API.

00:50:21.096 --> 00:50:26.336 A:middle
And let me conclude with a
short demo of that in action.

00:50:30.056 --> 00:50:32.926 A:middle
So let's switch to
our demo device.

00:50:33.546 --> 00:50:38.966 A:middle
And I'm going to go to
the Photos application.

00:50:40.376 --> 00:50:43.906 A:middle
And here is the image
that has been just applied

00:50:43.906 --> 00:50:47.056 A:middle
or just has been edited by
Karl with this Sepia filter.

00:50:47.896 --> 00:50:50.746 A:middle
Now it turns out that this
simple app is actually vending a

00:50:50.746 --> 00:50:51.936 A:middle
